@*
    Example 1 — Basic usage.

    The minimum viable select: a label and a slug list. The control
    resolves "medium" as the initial active size (since "medium" is in
    the list) and sets data-text-size="medium" on <html>.

    The status line is part of the pattern, not an extra. The control is
    an icon button: it shows only the "A" glyph and its accessible name
    is always the Label ("Text size"), never the active size name — so
    without this line neither a sighted user nor a screen reader can
    read the current selection back off the closed control. See
    docs/accessibility.md.

    aria-live="polite" announces mutations only, so this stays silent on
    first paint and speaks once on each subsequent change — exactly what
    a text-size switch warrants (it is not an interruption).

    It is rendered visible on purpose: sighted users need the selection
    echoed too, and visible text helps cognitive accessibility. If a
    design genuinely cannot spare the space, keep the element and hide
    it with a visually-hidden (sr-only) class rather than deleting it —
    see docs/styling.md for the recipe.

    The CSS that actually resizes the page is yours; see the mapping in
    docs/styling.md. Use relative units on :root so every descendant
    inherits, or the user's choice is silently ignored (WCAG 1.4.4).
*@

@page "/examples/text-size-select/basic"
@rendermode InteractiveServer
@using LilyDesignSystem.Blazor.Helpers

<TextSizeSelect
    Label="Text size"
    Sizes="@Sizes"
    @bind-Value="size" />

<p class="text-size-select-status" aria-live="polite">
    Text size: @SizeLabel(size)
</p>

@code {
    private static readonly string[] Sizes =
        new[] { "small", "medium", "large", "x-large" };

    private string size = "";

    // SizeName is the component's own title-casing rule, exported so the
    // status line reads "X Large", not "x-large", and can never drift
    // from the option labels. If you pass a SizeLabels dictionary to the
    // select, look the label up in that same dictionary instead.
    private static string SizeLabel(string slug) =>
        string.IsNullOrEmpty(slug) ? "none" : TextSizeSelect.SizeName(slug);
}
